replyContent: The app isnt a subscription. Twitter limits the amount of times 3rd party apps can access it's services in a 15 min interval. This is called rate limiting. This is twitters policy, theres no way around it, except to wait the 15 mins, then you will be able to access it again. If you check out the FAQ section in settings, it goes into detail on this.

It stinks because I love Talon and I love Klinker and their apps. My lifestyle means that I have to use multiple devices on multiple platforms daily and Tweetmarker (or even just some sort of multi-device position marking system) is important to me, and Talon is so inconsistent with how it uses it. It's been a problem for several years (my previous review from 2 years ago also referenced this problem) too. I'm sure I'll bounce back to Talon at some point since Luke is an awesome developer. If you don't need position marking, by all means Talon is an awesome Twitter client.

content: Great feeling UI, bad UX. Runs smooth, looks slick, and has a few good features over the regular twitter client. Unfortunately the experience of using Talon is simply a chore. Tap tap tap. So many extra taps to do basic tasks. Hardly any options for tweaking outside of font choices/colors, so what you see is what you get. Liking/RT requires you to expand a tweet or tap a small hidden area for quick actions - it would be far quicker to simply have small buttons already in the timeline, or at least able to quickly expand without having to tap a tiny area (with no icon indicating it is there, I only discovered it by accident). Expanding a tweet in a conversation, for whatever reason, only loads the first 2-3 tweets. You have to then tap "show all" to actually see the conversation that the expanded tweet is a part of. I'm unsure why the developer just doesn't show the full conversation on the first tap. On top of that, conversations are unintuitively shown. When you tap a tweet in a conversation, it doesn't show the tweet & its place within the conversation, it shows the tweet isolated, requiring you to tap "show all" again to see the full conversation. Talon is form over function.
Since the last update, I can no longer see who retweeted me when I click on an individual tweet. How can I fix this?
replyContent: Just hit the three dot overflow button on the tweet, it is there.

I feel this could use some constructive criticism. For me this app is almost perfect, yes I know you have your own push/pull service, but if you want to compete with Fenix you'll need to add some essentials that I feel are missing; 1: Search. The ability to search for handles/names as you're composing them, you might not know what a certain persons' @handle is or you may not already follow them and you would be helped if Talon searched twitter as you typed it, very much like Fenix does.  2. Make it more obvious when you're looking at a collection of multiple images in one packet or just one image tweeted, for example, if you click on a tweet with four images, sometimes it's not clear whether you can click through to the individual images, or whether it's a collage of 4 pictures together in one.  3. Swipe to compose is fantastic for speedy tweets, I know you have a swipe from the edge of the screen for an option, if you could give us an option to change that to compose tweet, that would be awesome, it's especially good in landscape mode  4. Remember previous hash-tags, so that an auto-fill option becomes available when you type them, or something similar.  Overall Brilliant!

Why is the unread tweet count backwards? It's counts up unread tweets when you move away from the most current tweet and doesn't show you remaining tweets as you scroll to the current tweet.   This is exactly opposite behavior to how classic talon works which is the correct manner.
replyContent: It isn't meant to work like the classic. As you scroll up to view new content, everything gets out of the way for you so you take the full screen to view it. Then scrolling back down will show you the information
